chunks.text: get is one of the critical technologies during on-orbit autonomous close proximity operation missions [1,2], such as near-field rendezvous, approaching, flying around and capturing. These un-cooperative targets are usually without prior informa-
tion about their structural and inertial parameters, nor artificial markers located known positions on the target. Therefore, the relative state and inertia proper-

ties are complete unknown. For a safe close proximity operation mission, such like approach to and capture the target, the relative state can provide important navi- gation information for the control strategy. Besides, the information of the target’s

inertia properties is necessary to propagate its state and can be used in the motion prediction before capture and de-spun control design after capture. In the past few decades, many vision-based estimation methods were devel-

oped [3–6] for un-cooperative targets. Terui et al. [7] estimated the relative pose for a non-cooperative targets based on model matching method. This method uses a stereo vision measurement system to obtain point cloud measurements of non-
cooperative targets, and uses ICP algorithm to obtain the estimation of the rel- ative state. Based on stereo vision measurement, Biondi et al. [8] estimated the

centroid of a large non-cooperative target by kinematic registration method. Jiang et al. [9] estimated the state, feature point position and inertial parameters of un- cooperative targets using constrained extended Kalman filtering according to the

3D position measurement of several feature points extracted from stereo vision. Physical constraints between these vectors constructed from the feature points make the system observable. Based on the measurement of several feature points on

the un-cooperative target, Segal et al. [10] proposed an iterated extended Kalman filter algorithm to estimate the relative state in each mode, combined with sev- eral modes of the predetermined un-cooperative target inertia tensor. Finally, the

optimal inertia tensor and pose parameter estimates of un-cooperative targets are obtained according to the maximum a posteriori (MAP) estimation. Dong and Zhu [11] presented a method to estimate the relative state of a un-cooperative target
with some known feature point by a monocular camera, and the ground exper- iments are conducted to verify the estimation results. Tweddle [13] developed a

SLAM solution to get the full information of a spinning un-cooperative target, with high computation complexity. Lichter and Dubowsky [12] estimated the state using thousands of 3D points by several cooperative 3D sensors, which leads to
heavy computational efforts. To overcome the constraints produced in the inertial parameters, an inno- vative stereo vision-based algorithm is developed in this paper to get the rela-

The relative attitude quaternion of the un-cooperative target and the initial value of the relative attitude of the geometry coordinate system are set to the true value, the initial value of the inertia parameter and the relative position

of the centroid system are set to zero, and the initial values of the other state components are added the initial standard deviation of the filter on the basis of their true values. The error of a simulation result in 200 Monte Carlo simulations
Under the given centroid position and attitude measurement noise level, the designed EKF algorithm can effectively estimate the relative state, iner-
tial parameters and centroid position and attitude of un-cooperative targets, and they all converge to their respective 3  sigma  bounds. It can be seen that all

the state estimate can achieve high estimation accuracy. The relative attitude estimate error is no more than 0 . 4 ◦ , and the inertia angular velocity estimate error of the target is within 5 × 10 − 5  rad / s. The relative position and linear veloc-

ity estimation errors of each axis do not exceed 0 . 01 m  and 10  μ m, respectively. The inertial parameters converge to within 0 . 02, and the single-axis position and attitude errors of the geometry frame are controlled at 0 . 001 m and 0 . 04 ◦ .
Aiming at the equality/inequality constraints existing in the existing inertia parameter modeling methods, this paper proposes a new inertia parameter mod-

eling method, which uses the inverse hyperbolic tangent function to parameterize the inertial ratios. By this way, the inertial parameters are independent random variables without constraints, which is a key contribution of this paper. The sim-

ulation results show that, based on the geometry frame constructed by random three non-collinear feature points on the un-cooperative target, the developed algorithm can estimate effectively the relative attitude, inertial angular velocity,
relative position, relative linear velocity, inertial parameters and position and attitude deviation of geometry frame of the un-cooperative target.
